    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-09-30T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-09-30T05:00:00-05:00" n="588"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d588">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/10335: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-30T18:00:00+08:00"
                            >September 30, 1937—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 30—10:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>741. Commander-in-Chief reported in his despatch 0024–1610 attacks upon Chinese
                    fishing fleets off southern coast. Further details are reported in Hong Kong’s
                    telegram of September 29, 4 p.m.<note n="21" xml:id="d588fn21">Not
                        printed.</note> This action, it seems to me, merits some comment by us in
                    any case and representations [to] that effect made to the Japanese Government as
                    being contrary to ordinary international practice.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
